{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f551d1a-cf2c-4158-b887-b2c0e817d89b","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues to fix before publishing:\n\n**Critical:**\n- **`choices` format is wrong** — Must be an array, not an object:\n  ```json\n  \"choices\": [\n    { \"choice\": \"net8.0\", \"description\": \".NET 8\" },\n    { \"choice\": \"net9.0\", \"description\": \".NET 9\" }\n  ]\n  ```\n\n**Recommended:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation support.\n- **Missing `replaces`** on the `Framework` symbol — Without it, the chosen value won't substitute anything in the project files.\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for template discoverability and grouping on NuGet.\n- **Missing `precedence`** — Useful for versioning when users have multiple versions installed.\n\n**Not ready as-is** — the `choices` format error will cause the parameter to malfunction at runtime.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a043a43-1ccb-4887-9d86-bf5020b92c07","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check against the .NET template engine requirements:\n\nRequired fields:\n- `$schema` - Missing! Should reference the template.json schema for validation.\n- `author` - ✅ Present (\"My Company\")\n- `classifications` - ✅ Present\n- `identity` - ✅ Present\n- `name` - ✅ Present\n- `shortName` - ✅ Present\n- `sourceName` - ✅ Present (used for renaming)\n- `tags` - ✅ Present with language and type\n\n\n- `groupIdentity` - Missing, which is recommended for organizing related templates\n- `precedence` - Missing, useful for handling multiple template versions\n\nI'm also noticing the `Framework` symbol uses an object format for choices, but the newer template engine versions prefer arrays—though the current format might still be compatible.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider the choices format. The correct structure should use an array where each choice object includes both the `choice` key and its `description`, not a nested object format. The object key-value approach wouldn't work properly with the template engine and could cause issues. The `Framework` symbol is also missing a `replaces` property, so it won't actually substitute the framework moniker in the project files unless I add something like `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` to handle that replacement.","outputTokens":1014,"requestId":"7401:2EF3EB:1DE5152:20F4B77:69FA9192"},"id":"584d254d-4de3-4894-95b9-8d14b06d474c","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:56:12.811Z","parentId":"3a07959a-b6b6-45b3-8712-2f9ed9b35c3d"}
